# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eigrp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Router vendors typically design their routers to assign a default administrative distance to each kind of route.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] For example, on Cisco routers, routes issued by the Open Shortest Path First routing protocol have a lower default administrative distance than routes issued by the Routing Information Protocol.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] This is because, by default on Cisco routers, OSPF has a default administrative distance of 110 and RIP has a default administrative distance of 120.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Administrative distance values can, however, usually be adjusted manually by a network administrator.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The administrative distance (AD) value is assigned by the router on a per-protocol basis.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Routers, by design, should not install multiple routes into the routing table as this has the potential to cause routing loops.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] While a router may run multiple routing protocols on the same device, it is necessary for the router to implement a process to ensure that multiple routes, pointing to the same destination do not simultaneously exist in the routing table.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Each process running on a router advertises its administrative distance value to the local router.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The router uses this value to determine which route should be used.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Once a route has been selected, the routing information database is updated.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] If two routes have the same administrative distance, the router uses its vendor-specific algorithm to determine which route should be installed.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Cisco routers simply ignore the values and fall back to the default values, which are never the same.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The router will usually compare administrative distances to determine which protocol has the lowest value.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The router prefers protocols that have a lower assigned administrative distance.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] For example, OSPF has a default distance of 110, so it is preferred by the router process, over RIP, which has a default distance of 120.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The administrator can arbitrarily reconfigure the administrative distances, which affects the ranking of the preferred routes by the routing process.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] On Cisco routers, static routes have an administrative distance of 1, making them preferred over routes issued by a dynamic routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The administrative distance is a value that is always only referenced by the local router itself.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The administrative distance is not advertised on the network.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The following table lists the default administrative distances for various routing protocols used on Cisco routers.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] An administrative distance of 255 will cause the router to remove the route from the routing table and not use it.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The following table lists the default administrative distances for various routing protocols used on Juniper routers.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The following table lists the default administrative distances used on ExtremeXOS / Switch-Engine.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The following table lists the default administrative distances used on Extreme VOSS / Fabric-Engine.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The following table lists the default administrative distances for various routing protocols used on Fortinet FortiGate routers.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The network administrator may modify the administrative distance to change the desired ranking of routing protocols.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] This may be necessary in cases where multiple routing protocols are in use.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The Cisco Internetwork Operating System enables network administrators to modify the distance by changing the distance value in sub-router configuration mode.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] In the example below, RIP's administrative distance is changed to 89 so that it used in preference to OSPF.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Manually configuring the administrative distance is also required when configuring a floating static route.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Floating static routes are used to provide an alternate path when a primary link fails.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] In order for static routes to be configured as a backup, the static route's administrative distance would need to be adjusted.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Otherwise, it will take precedence over all routing protocols and routes issued from a routing protocol will not be inserted into the routing table.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The example below shows how to configure the administrative distance to 254 to specify that it should only be used as a last resort.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] In the event that two routing protocols are configured with the same administrative distance, the Cisco router will ignore the configured values and instead use the default values.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] Verifying the configuration of the administrative distance is done on Cisco equipment using the *show ip route* command in privileged exec mode on the console of the Cisco router.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] In the example shown below, the administrative distance is 1.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The letter "S" indicates that the route is a static route that has, for all intents and purposes, been added manually to the router process by the administrator and installed into the routing table.
[src:eigrp/administrative-distance] The *do show ip route* command will display the following, confirming that a static route has an administrative distance of 1.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] A **distance-vector routing protocol** in data networks determines the best route for data packets based on distance.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols measure the distance by the number of routers a packet has to pass; one router counts as one hop.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Some distance-vector protocols also take into account network latency and other factors that influence traffic on a given route.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] To determine the best route across a network, routers using a distance-vector protocol exchange information with one another, usually routing tables plus hop counts for destination networks and possibly other traffic information.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols also require that a router inform its neighbours of network topology changes periodically.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols use the Bellman–Ford algorithm to calculate the best route.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Another way of calculating the best route across a network is based on link cost, and is implemented through link-state routing protocols.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The term *distance vector* refers to the fact that the protocol manipulates *vectors* (arrays) of distances to other nodes in the network.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The distance vector algorithm was the original ARPANET routing algorithm and was implemented more widely in local area networks with the Routing Information Protocol (RIP).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] In these protocols, each router does not possess information about the full network topology.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It advertises its distance value (DV) calculated to other routers and receives similar advertisements from other routers unless changes are done in the local network or by neighbours (routers).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Using these routing advertisements each router populates its routing table.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] In the next advertisement cycle, a router advertises updated information from its routing table.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This process continues until the routing tables of each router converge to stable values.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Some of these protocols have the disadvantage of slow convergence.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers that use distance-vector protocol determine the distance between themselves and a destination.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The best route for data through a data network is measured in terms of the numbers of routers (hops) a packet has to pass through to reach its destination network.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Additionally, some distance-vector protocols take into account other traffic information, such as network latency.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] To establish the best route, routers regularly exchange information with neighbouring routers, usually their routing table, hop count for a destination network and possibly other traffic related information.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers that implement distance-vector protocol rely purely on the information provided to them by other routers, and do not assess the network topology.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector protocols update the routing tables of routers and determine the route on which a packet will be sent by the *next hop* which is the exit interface of the router and the IP address of the interface of the receiving router.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance is a measure of the cost to reach a certain node.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The least cost route between any two nodes is the route with minimum distance.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Updates are performed periodically in a distance-vector protocol where all or part of a router's routing table is sent to all its neighbours that are configured to use the same distance-vector routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Once a router has this information it is able to amend its own routing table to reflect the changes and then inform its neighbours of the changes.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This process has been described as ‘routing by rumour’ because routers are relying on the information they receive from other routers and cannot determine if the information is actually valid and true.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] There are a number of features which can be used to help with instability and inaccurate routing information.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The oldest routing protocol, and the oldest distance-vector protocol, is version 1 of the Routing Information Protocol (RIPv1).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIPv1 was formally standardised in 1988.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It establishes the shortest path across a network purely on the basis of the hops, that is numbers of routers that need to be passed to reach the destination network.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIP is an interior gateway protocol, so it can be used in local area networks (LANs) on interior or border routers.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers with RIPv1 implementation exchange their routing tables with neighbouring routers by broadcasting a RIPv1 packet every 30 second into all connected networks.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIPv1 is not suitable for large networks as it limits the number of hops to 15.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This hop limit was introduced to avoid routing loops, but also means that networks that are connected through more than 15 routers are unreachable.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The distance-vector protocol designed for use in wide area networks (WANs) is the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] BGP is an exterior gateway protocol and therefore implemented on border and exterior routers on the Internet.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It exchanges information between routers through a Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) session.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers with BGP implementation determine the shortest path across a network based on a range of factors other than hops.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] BGP can also be configured by administrators so that certain routes are preferred or avoided.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] BGP is used by internet service providers (ISPs) and telecommunication companies.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Among the distance-vector protocols that have been described as a hybrid, because it uses routing methods associated with link-state routing protocols, is the proprietary Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It was developed by Cisco in the 1980s and was designed to offer better convergence and cause less network traffic between routers than the link-state routing protocol Open Shortest Path First (OSPF).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Another example of a distance-vector routing protocol is Babel.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The Bellman–Ford algorithm does not prevent routing loops from happening and suffers from the **count to infinity problem**.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The core of the count to infinity problem is that if A tells B that it has a path somewhere, there is no way for B to know if the path has B as a part of it.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] To see the problem, imagine a subnet connected like A–B–C–D–E–F, and let the metric between the routers be "number of jumps".
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] In the vector-update-process B notices that the route to A, which was distance 1, is down – B does not receive the vector update from A.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The problem is, B also gets an update from C, and C is still not aware of the fact that A is down – so it tells B that A is only two jumps from C (C to B to A).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Since B doesn't know that the path from C to A is through itself (B), it updates its table with the new value "B to A = 2 + 1".
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Later on, B forwards the update to C and due to the fact that A is reachable through B (From C's point of view), C decides to update its table to "C to A = 3 + 1".
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This slowly propagates through the network until it becomes infinity (in which case the algorithm corrects itself, due to the relaxation property of Bellman-Ford).
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIP uses the split horizon with poison reverse technique to reduce the chance of forming loops and uses a maximum number of hops to counter the 'count to infinity' problem.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] These measures avoid the formation of routing loops in some, but not all, cases.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The addition of a *hold time* (refusing route updates for a few minutes after a route retraction) avoids loop formation in virtually all cases, but causes a significant increase in convergence times.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] More recently, a number of loop-free distance vector protocols have been developed — notable examples are EIGRP, DSDV and Babel.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] These avoid loop formation in all cases, but suffer from increased complexity, and their deployment has been slowed down by the success of link state routing protocols such as OSPF.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] We mark the current time (or iteration) in the algorithm with T, and begin (at time 0, or T=0) by creating distance matrices for each router to its immediate neighbours.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] As we build the routing tables below, the shortest path is highlighted in green, and a new shortest path is highlighted in yellow.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Grey columns indicate nodes that are not neighbors of the current node, and are therefore not considered as a valid direction in its table.
[src:eigrp/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Red indicates invalid entries in the table since they refer to distances from a node to itself, or via itself.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP is used on a router to share routes with other routers within the same autonomous system.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Unlike other well known routing protocols, such as RIP, EIGRP only sends incremental updates, reducing the workload on the router and the amount of data that needs to be transmitted.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP replaced the Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (IGRP) in 1993.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] One of the major reasons for this was the change to classless IPv4 addresses in the Internet Protocol, which IGRP could not support.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Almost all routers contain a routing table that contains rules by which traffic is forwarded in a network.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] If the router does not contain a valid path to the destination, the traffic is discarded.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP is a dynamic routing protocol by which routers automatically share route information.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This eases the workload on a network administrator who does not have to configure changes to the routing table manually.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Information in the topology table may be inserted into the router's routing table and can then be used to forward traffic.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] If the network changes (for example, a physical link fails or is disconnected), the path will become unavailable.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP is designed to detect these changes and will attempt to find a new path to the destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The old path that is no longer available is removed from the routing table.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Unlike most distance vector routing protocols, EIGRP does not transmit all the data in the router's routing table when a change is made, but will only transmit the changes that have been made since the routing table was last updated.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP does not send its routing table periodically, but will only send routing table data when an actual change has occurred.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This behavior is more inline with link-state routing protocols, thus EIGRP is mostly considered a hybrid protocol.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] When a router running EIGRP is connected to another router also running EIGRP, information is exchanged between the two routers.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] They form a relationship, known as an *adjacency*.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The entire routing table is exchanged between both routers at this time.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] After the exchange has completed, only differential changes are sent.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP is often considered a hybrid protocol because it also sends link state updates when link states change.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Example of setting up EIGRP on a Cisco IOS router for a private network.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The 0.0.15.255 wildcard in this example indicates a subnetwork with a maximum of 4094 hosts—it is the bitwise complement of the subnet mask 255.255.240.0.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The **no auto-summary** command prevents automatic route summarization on classful boundaries, which would otherwise result in routing loops in discontiguous networks.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP is a distance vector & Link State routing protocol that uses the diffusing update algorithm (DUAL) (based on work from SRI International) to improve the efficiency of the protocol and to help prevent calculation errors when attempting to determine the best path to a remote network.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP determines the value of the path using five metrics: bandwidth, load, delay, reliability and MTU.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP uses five different messages to communicate with its neighbor routers – Hello, Update, Query, Reply, and Acknowledgement.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP routing information, exchanged to a router from another router within the same autonomous system, has a default administrative distance of 90.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP routing information, that has come from an EIGRP-enabled router outside the autonomous system, has a default administrative distance of 170.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP does not operate using the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This means that EIGRP does not use a port number to identify traffic.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Rather, EIGRP is designed to work on top of Layer 3 (i.e. the IP protocol).
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Since EIGRP does not use TCP for communication, it implements Cisco's Reliable Transport Protocol (RTP) to ensure that EIGRP router updates are delivered to all neighbors completely.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The Reliable Transport Protocol also contains other mechanisms to maximize efficiency and support multicasting.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP uses 224.0.0.10 as its multicast address and protocol number 88.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Cisco Systems now classifies EIGRP as a distance vector routing protocol, but it is normally said to be a hybrid routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] While EIGRP is an advanced routing protocol that combines many of the features of both link-state and distance-vector routing protocols, EIGRP's DUAL algorithm contains many features which make it more of a distance vector routing protocol than a link-state routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Minimum Bandwidth (in kilobits per second) along the path from router to destination network.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Number of routers a packet passes through when routing to a remote network, used to limit the EIGRP AS.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP maintains a hop count for every route, however, the hop count is not used in metric calculation.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] It is only verified against a predefined maximum on an EIGRP router (by default it is set to 100 and can be changed to any value between 1 and 255).
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Routes having a hop count higher than the maximum will be advertised as unreachable by an EIGRP router.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The composite routing metric calculation uses five parameters, so-called K values, K1 through K5.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] These act as multipliers or modifiers in the composite metric calculation.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] By default, only total delay and minimum bandwidth are considered when EIGRP is started on a router, but an administrator can enable or disable all the K values as needed to consider the other Vector metrics.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] where the various constants ( $K_{1}$ through $K_{5}$ ) can be set by the user to produce varying behaviors.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] An important and unintuitive fact is that if $K_{5}$ is set to zero, the term ${\tfrac {K_{5}}{K_{4}+{\text{Reliability}}}}$ **is not used (i.e. taken as 1)**.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The default is for $K_{1}$ and $K_{3}$ to be set to 1, and the rest to zero, effectively reducing the above formula to $({\text{Bandwidth}}_{E}+{\text{Delay}}_{E})\cdot 256$ .
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Obviously, these constants must be set to the same value on all routers in an EIGRP system, or permanent routing loops may result.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Cisco routers running EIGRP will not form an EIGRP adjacency and will complain about K-values mismatch until these values are identical on these routers.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] On Cisco routers, the interface bandwidth is a configurable static parameter expressed in kilobits per second (setting this only affects metric calculation and not actual line bandwidth).
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] 10 Gbit/s) by the interface bandwidth statement value yields a result that is used in the weighted formula.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The interface delay is a configurable static parameter expressed in tens of microseconds.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP takes this value directly without scaling into the weighted formula.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] However, various *show* commands display the interface delay in microseconds.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Therefore, if given a delay value in microseconds, it must first be divided by 10 before using it in the weighted formula.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] IGRP uses the same basic formula for computing the overall metric, the only difference is that in IGRP, the formula does not contain the scaling factor of 256.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] In fact, this scaling factor was introduced as a simple means to facilitate backward compatility between EIGRP and IGRP: In IGRP, the overall metric is a 24-bit value while EIGRP uses a 32-bit value to express this metric.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] By multiplying a 24-bit value with the factor of 256 (effectively bit-shifting it 8 bits to the left), the value is extended into 32 bits, and vice versa.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This way, redistributing information between EIGRP and IGRP involves simply dividing or multiplying the metric value by a factor of 256, which is done automatically.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] A feasible successor for a particular destination is a next hop router that is guaranteed not to be a part of a routing loop.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This condition is verified by testing the feasibility condition.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Thus, every successor is also a feasible successor.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] However, in most references about EIGRP the term *feasible successor* is used to denote only those routes which provide a loop-free path but which are not successors (i.e. they do not provide the least distance).
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] From this point of view, for a reachable destination, there is always at least one successor, however, there might not be any feasible successors.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] A feasible successor provides a working route to the same destination, although with a higher distance.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] At any time, a router can send a packet to a destination marked "Passive" through any of its successors or feasible successors without alerting them in the first place, and this packet will be delivered properly.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Feasible successors are also recorded in the topology table.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The feasible successor effectively provides a backup route in the case that existing successors become unavailable.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Also, when performing unequal-cost load-balancing (balancing the network traffic in inverse proportion to the cost of the routes), the feasible successors are used as next hops in the routing table for the load-balanced destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] By default, the total count of successors and feasible successors for a destination stored in the routing table is limited to four.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This limit can be changed in the range from 1 to 6.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] In more recent versions of Cisco IOS (e.g.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] A destination in the topology table can be marked either as *passive* or *active*.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] A passive state is a state when the router has identified the successor(s) for the destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The destination changes to *active* state when the current successor no longer satisfies the feasibility condition and there are no feasible successors identified for that destination (i.e. no backup routes are available).
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The destination changes back from *active* to *passive* when the router received replies to all queries it has sent to its neighbors.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The feasibility condition is a sufficient condition for loop freedom in EIGRP-routed network.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] It is used to select the successors and feasible successors that are guaranteed to be on a loop-free route to a destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] If, for a destination, a neighbor router advertises a distance that is strictly lower than our feasible distance, then this neighbor lies on a loop-free route to this destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] If, for a destination, a neighbor router tells us that it is closer to the destination than we have ever been, then this neighbor lies on a loop-free route to this destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] It is important to realize that this condition is a sufficient, not a necessary, condition.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] That means that neighbors which satisfy this condition are guaranteed to be on a loop-free path to some destination, however, there may be also other neighbors on a loop-free path which do not satisfy this condition.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] However, such neighbors do not provide the shortest path to a destination, therefore, not using them does not present any significant impairment of the network functionality.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] These neighbors will be re-evaluated for possible usage if the router transitions to Active state for that destination.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP features load balancing on paths with different costs.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] A multiplier, called variance, is used to determine which paths to include into load balancing.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The variance is set to 1 by default, which means load balancing on equal cost paths.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The minimum metric of a route is multiplied by the variance value.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Each path with a metric that is smaller than the result is used in load balancing.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] With the functionality of the Unequal Path Cost Load Balancing on EIGRP, OSPF protocol is unable to design the network by Unequal Path Cost Load Balancing.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Regarding the Unequal Path Cost Load Balancing function on industry usage, the network design can be flexible with the traffic management.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Cisco released details of the proprietary EIGRP routing protocol in an RFC in an effort to assist companies whose networks operate in a multi-vendor environment.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP was developed 20 years ago, yet it is still one of the primary Cisco routing protocols due to its purported usability and scalability in comparison to other protocols.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Cisco has stated that EIGRP is an open standard but they leave out several core details in the RFC definition which makes interoperability hard to set up between different vendors' routers when the protocol is used.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Even Cisco NX-OS for example does not support unequal cost load balancing.
[src:eigrp/enhanced-interior-gateway-routing-protocol] As of 2022 EIGRP has alpha support in FRRouting and it seems to be generally unsupported by other routing software.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] IGRP was created in part to overcome the limitations of RIP (maximum hop count of only 15, and a single routing metric) when used within large networks.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] IGRP supports multiple metrics for each route, including bandwidth, delay, load, and reliability; to compare two routes these metrics are combined into a single metric, using a formula which can be adjusted through the use of pre-set constants.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] By default, the IGRP composite metric is a sum of the segment delays and the lowest segment bandwidth.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] The maximum configurable hop count of IGRP-routed packets is 255 (default 100), and routing updates are broadcast every 90 seconds (by default).
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] IGRP uses protocol number 9 for communication.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] IGRP is considered a classful routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Because the protocol has no field for a subnet mask, the router assumes that all subnetwork addresses within the same Class A, Class B, or Class C network have the same subnet mask as the subnet mask configured for the interfaces in question.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] This contrasts with classless routing protocols that can use variable length subnet masks.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] Classful protocols have become less popular as they are wasteful of IP address space.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] In order to address the issues of address space and other factors, Cisco created EIGRP (Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol).
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP adds support for VLSM (variable length subnet mask) and adds the Diffusing Update Algorithm (DUAL) in order to improve routing and provide a loopless environment.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] EIGRP has completely replaced IGRP, making IGRP an obsolete routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] In Cisco IOS versions 12.3 and greater, IGRP is completely unsupported.
[src:eigrp/interior-gateway-routing-protocol] In the new Cisco CCNA curriculum (version 4), IGRP is mentioned only briefly, as an "obsolete protocol".
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] A **routing protocol** specifies how routers communicate with each other to distribute information that enables them to select paths between nodes on a computer network.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Routers perform the traffic directing functions on the Internet; data packets are forwarded through the networks of the internet from router to router until they reach their destination computer.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Routing algorithms determine the specific choice of route.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Each router has a prior knowledge only of networks attached to it directly.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] A routing protocol shares this information first among immediate neighbors, and then throughout the network.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] This way, routers gain knowledge of the topology of the network.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] The ability of routing protocols to dynamically adjust to changing conditions such as disabled connections and components and route data around obstructions is what gives the Internet its fault tolerance and high availability.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Certain additional characteristics such as multilayer interfacing may also be employed as a means of distributing uncompromised networking gateways to authorized ports.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] This has the added benefit of preventing issues with routing protocol loops.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Many routing protocols are defined in technical standards documents called RFCs.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Interior gateway protocols (IGPs) exchange routing information within a single routing domain.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Exterior gateway protocols exchange routing information between autonomous systems.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Many software implementations exist for most of the common routing protocols.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Examples of open-source applications are Bird Internet routing daemon, Quagga, GNU Zebra, OpenBGPD, OpenOSPFD, and XORP.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Some network certification courses distinguish between routing protocols and *routed* protocols.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] A **routed protocol** is used to deliver application traffic.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] It provides appropriate addressing information in its internet layer or network layer to allow a packet to be forwarded from one network to another.
[src:eigrp/routing-protocol] Examples of routed protocols are the Internet Protocol (IP) and Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:eigrp/routing-table] In computer networking, a **routing table**, or **routing information base** (**RIB**), is a data table stored in a router or a network host that lists the routes to particular network destinations, and in some cases, metrics (distances) associated with those routes.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The routing table contains information about the topology of the network immediately around it.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The construction of routing tables is the primary goal of routing protocols.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Static routes are entries that are fixed, rather than resulting from routing protocols and network topology discovery procedures.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] A routing table is analogous to a distribution map in package delivery.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Whenever a node needs to send data to another node on a network, it must first know *where* to send it.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] If the node cannot directly connect to the destination node, it has to send it via other nodes along a route to the destination node.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Each node needs to keep track of which way to deliver various packages of data, and for this, it uses a routing table.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] A routing table is a database that keeps track of paths, like a map, and uses these to determine which way to forward traffic.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] A routing table is a data file in RAM that is used to store route information about directly connected and remote networks.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Nodes can also share the contents of their routing table with other nodes.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The primary function of a router is to forward a packet toward its destination network, which is the destination IP address of the packet.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] To do this, a router needs to search the routing information stored in its routing table.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The routing table contains network/next hop associations.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] These associations tell a router that a particular destination can be optimally reached by sending the packet to a specific router that represents the next hop on the way to the final destination.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The next hop association can also be the outgoing or exit interface to the final destination.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] With hop-by-hop routing, each routing table lists, for all reachable destinations, the address of the next device along the path to that destination: the next hop.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Assuming that the routing tables are consistent, the simple algorithm of relaying packets to their destination's next hop thus suffices to deliver data anywhere in a network.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Hop-by-hop is the fundamental characteristic of the IP Internet layer and the OSI Network Layer.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] When a router interface is configured with an IP address and subnet mask, the interface becomes a host on that attached network.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] A directly connected network is a network that is directly attached to one of the router interfaces.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The network address and subnet mask of the interface, along with the interface type and number, are entered into the routing table as a directly connected network.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] A remote network is a network that can only be reached by sending the packet to another router.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Routing table entries to remote networks may be either dynamic or static.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Dynamic routes are routes to remote networks that were learned automatically by the router through a dynamic routing protocol.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Static routes are routes that a network administrator manually configured.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Routing tables are also a key aspect of certain security operations, such as unicast reverse path forwarding (uRPF).
[src:eigrp/routing-table] In this technique, which has several variants, the router also looks up, in the routing table, the *source address* of the packet.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] If there exists no route back to the source address, the packet is assumed to be malformed or involved in a network attack and is dropped.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The need to record routes to large numbers of devices using limited storage space represents a major challenge in routing table construction.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] On the Internet, the currently dominant address aggregation technology is a bitwise prefix matching scheme called Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Supernetworks can also be used to help control routing table size.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] *metric*: The routing metric of the path through which the packet is to be sent.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] The route will go in the direction of the gateway with the lowest metric.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] *interface*: Such as eth0 for the first Ethernet card, eth1 for the second Ethernet card, etc.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] Routing tables are generally not used directly for packet forwarding in modern router architectures; instead, they are used to generate the information for a simpler forwarding table.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] This forwarding table contains only the routes that are chosen by the routing algorithm as preferred routes for packet forwarding.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] It is often in a compressed or pre-compiled format that is optimized for hardware storage and lookup.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] This router architecture separates the control plane function of the routing table from the forwarding plane function of the forwarding table.
[src:eigrp/routing-table] This separation of control and forwarding provides uninterrupted high-performance forwarding.
